<div class="header">Description</div>
{{Blurimage|file=Infohazard_complex.webp|hovertext=You know.|caption=The most infamous photo of Level 959.|width=420px}}
{{Blurimage|file=Infohazard_complex_2.webp|hovertext=known|caption=[unknown]|width=420px}}
All known accounts from the few who briefly escaped '''Level 959''' describe a series of outmoded office spaces of mostly uniform qualities. An invasive, dull-yellow lacquers the walls and ceilings, while a bloodshot carpet surfaces the floor. A fluorescent ceiling light or two feebly illuminates each room, with any outreaching corridors shrouded in darkness. Each room boxes in the level's hapless victims with low-hanging ceilings and cramped widths. All rooms in the level take on either a square or rectangular shape. Doors conceal most corridors within the level, opening which are often exasperating.

One may rarely encounter an upward staircase, leading to a ravenous gloom above. The second floor of '''Level 959''' is identical in layout and appearance to the first, with the primary exception of the total lack of light. On the second floor, some rooms are left without a ceiling, leading straight into [[The Void]], while some rooms may sport a pitfall where one falls indefinitely until they die from Nonpentennism. Windows on the first floor seep light into these pitfalls, allowing one to detect them, provided they consistently look down. This floor bears an anomaly causing devices with batteries to consume tenfold more energy, incentivizing mindful usage of phones, flashlights, and the like.

'''Level 959''' lacks any air circulation, and temperatures stay at a constant 17°C, with the upper floor at 9°C. All surfaces within the level are about 5-6°C<ref>The Fahrenheit conversions are 62.6°F, 48.2°F, and 9-10.2°F respectively.</ref> colder than the air they enclose. Walls and ceilings are slightly sticky to the touch. The odor of burnt meat pervades the atmosphere of the lower floors. Office apparatus are sparse within '''Level 959''', ranging from pens and unintelligible paper documents to chairs and desks topped with fully functional desktop setups. Among these objects is [[Object 1|Almond Water]], which delays Nonpentennism by one stage upon consuming two full bottles.

Smaller, unconventionally styled spaces are uncommon throughout '''Level 959''', seen behind sliding glass doors. Characterized by singular shelves and horizontal metal poles, they closely resemble unfinished walk-in closets. Some closets contain coat hangers, empty drawers, and tattered articles of clothing. Their smell is akin to a brand-new car, overpowering the odor of the parent room once the glass doors are opened. They exude high temperatures relative to the level, at around 29°C. Walking into these rooms exponentially speeds up Nonpentennism to where one dies in mere minutes. It is thought that merely staring at these closets considerably speeds up the infohazard's onset.

Isolative properties exist in '''Level 959''', but they are dissimilar to [[Phenomenon 15]]. One cannot sense others and their belongings in the level, and two wanderers can phase through each other. However, one is able to see the impact that others have on the level, such as the light from a phone or flashlight, the booting up of a terminal, and even the sounds of footsteps. This results in instances where carrying an object native to '''Level 959''' causes it to appear inexplicably levitating to others. Given specific circumstances, wanderers may shoddily communicate through the objects found on the level.<ref>One of these scenarios is where two wanderers in the same room exchanging messages via pen and paper.</ref>

Nothing in '''Level 959''' emanates any sound. Any sounds from wanderers, such as footsteps, will be amplified and may echo for several seconds depending on the circumstances. Sounds are trapped in their origin room and do not enter any linked hallways, staircases, or closets. The pitfalls on '''Level 959''' may radiate random noises<ref>The most commonly reported noises include distant gunshots, bird noises from the Frontrooms, thunderclaps, and ticking clocks.</ref> which often ring throughout their surroundings. 

'''Level 959'''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s gravity is slightly greater than that of Earth and the rest of the Backrooms by at most 30%. Due to this anomaly, wanderers incur a variety of minor afflictions ranging from minor height loss<ref>In '''Level 959'''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s gravity, wanderers shrink 1 centimeter (.4 in).</ref> to increased blood pressure. Past the third stage of Nonpentennism, victims stranded in '''Level 959''' are rendered unable to stand on two feet thanks to both the high gravity and physical weakness of the wanderer.

<div class="header">Nonpentennism</div>
The primary peril possessed by '''Level 959''' is its '''Nonpentennism''' infohazard. Any knowledge of the level, no matter how minute, will inflict the infohazard in any being, including both wanderers and certain entities. Such instances include entering the level and acknowledging its existence, or viewing a piece of information about the level in [[Level List|the Database]]. Those who escape '''Level 959''' do not necessarily escape '''Nonpentennism'''. As such, any information pertaining to the level in the Database has been redacted for public safety.

The wanderer will not notice any mental oddities the moment they contract '''Nonpentennism''', and will remain asymptomatic for about five days. During this grace period, the victim will either be greatly compelled to enter '''Level 959''', and if they fail to do so, they will instead noclip through the floor of their level. Throughout the next five days, the victim's mental and physical wellbeing will gradually worsen until their eventual demise. Shown below is a table of the stages of '''Nonpentennism''' that an afflicted wanderer will undergo.

