<br>
<div style="background:linear-gradient(to bottom, #FFFFFF 34px, #266C91 1px);background-size:40px 35px;"><div style="background:#C13720;margin-left:39px;"><div style="background:linear-gradient(to bottom, #FFFFFF 34px, #266C91 1px);background-size:35px 35px;line-height:35px;margin-left:1px;"><div style="background:linear-gradient(to bottom, #FFFFFF 34px, #266C91 1px);background-size:35px 35px;line-height:35px;margin-left:5px;margin-right:5px;"><br><span style="margin-left:35px"><span style="color:black; font-size:19.67px; font-family:Playwrite NG Modern;">
I've always had a knack for those absolute deadzone levels, most of the time it's just that they're filled to the brim with all sorts of nasty entities, and going there will just cause you to get ripped to shreds and all that. There's also those levels that used to be safe but then something happened and now they're all dangerous or something, like [[Level 116|<span style="font-family:Jua;">116</span>]] or [[Level 350|<span style="font-family:Playwrite NG Modern;">350</span>]].<br><br>But this one, Level 959, I have never in all my years in the Backrooms, came across a level this horrendous. Granted, you could just avoid the level altogether. There's just one thing though, there are so many possible entrances, that people who have never even heard of 959 can enter it and go through the horrors of nonpentonnon or whatever it was called. Simply the fact that it can start just by even mindlessly scrolling past the level slot is absolutely horrid, in my opinion.<br><br>It actually reminds me of something back in my time on [[The Frontrooms|<span style="font-family:Playwrite NG Modern;">Earth</span>]]. Since the internet was just starting to get big before I fell in, there were tons of crazy things on there, basically total anarchy. Really because it was a whole new frontier for everyone. There was this one thing that really drew my attention, "The Game".<br><br>The Game was basically some weird sort of mind thing, where basically, if you acknowledge its existence, you lose. And then once you lose you have to announce it or whatever. So then when I found out about Level 959's whole infohazardous property, I immediately remembered the whole thing with The Game. In fact, the more I think about it, Level 959 and The Game are so eerily similar. It's kind of disturbing to think that the Backrooms took the whole concept of it to make this hell of a level.<br><br>So now, while I'm writing this on a sheet of paper, I want any potential person who sees this to know.<br><br>Level 959 is The Game, and you just lost.
